<subSubSection pageId="130" pageNumber="527" type="distribution">
<caption inLine="true" pageId="130" pageNumber="527" targetBox="[119,709,2198,2611]" targetPageId="130">
<paragraph blockId="130.[732,1325,2191,2614]" pageId="130" pageNumber="527">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[733,909,2463,2496]" pageId="130" pageNumber="527">Distribution.</emphasis>
SE Ivory Coast, NE Ghana, C &amp; S Nigeria, WC Cameroon, and BiokoI.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="130" pageNumber="527" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="130.[732,1325,2191,2614]" pageId="130" pageNumber="527">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[734,1019,2541,2574]" pageId="130" pageNumber="527">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 90-109 mm, tail 53-64 mm, ear 9-14 mm,
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="130.[122,1327,2621,3284]" pageId="130" pageNumber="527">hindfoot 16-18 mm; weight 11-24 g. The Nigerian White-toothed Shrew is large. Dorsal pelage is very dark brown and grizzled, and ventral pelage is paler dark gray or grayish brown. Tail is 60-70% of head-body length, hairy, and dark brown. Skull is large and flat, with broad maxillary region and braincase; M” is large. There are three unicuspids. Chromosomal complement has 2n = 50 and FN = 76.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="130" pageNumber="527" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="130.[122,1327,2621,3284]" pageId="130" pageNumber="527">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[123,234,2826,2851]" pageId="130" pageNumber="527">Habitat.</emphasis>
Primarily rainforest habitats but also farms, grasslands, and relict forests in rainforest savanna mosaics and savanna in Ghana at elevations up to 600 m on Mount Cameroon.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
